[The EuroFlu bulletin for week 2/2013 (http://www.euroflu.org/cgi-files/bulletin_v2.cgi) stated the following. "Consultation rates for influenza-like illness (ILI) and/or acute respiratory infection (ARI) are now increasing in almost all countries in the Region. However, influenza activity is still largely limited to the western part of the Region, where widespread transmission is being reported by most countries currently. While influenza A(H1N1)pdm09, A(H3N2) and type B viruses are circulating in the Region, the proportion of influenza A(H1N1)pdm09 continues to increase, relative to influenza B and A(H3N2), and accounts for 84 percent of influenza A viruses subtyped. The number of reported hospitalizations due to severe acute respiratory infection (SARI) is increasing slowly along with a rising proportion of patients testing positive for influenza."

There are marked differences in the frequencies of the influenza virus types prevalent in different regions of the world. Overall the viruses in circulation globally are well-matched by the current vaccine virus strains, and no novel influenza viruses have made their appearance. There is some evidence that the consequences of influenza virus infection may be more severe than in previous years in some regions, but not overall. - Mod.CP.]
